{"index":65,"title":"disco: a toolkit for Distributional Control of Generative Models","abstract":"Pre-trained language models and other generative models have revolutionized NLP and beyond. However, these models tend to reproduce undesirable biases present in their training data. Also, they may overlook patterns that are important but challenging to capture. To address these limitations, researchers have introduced distributional control techniques. These techniques, not limited to language, allow controlling the prevalence (i.e. expectations) of any features of interest in the model\u2019s outputs. Despite their potential, the widespread adoption of these techniques has been hindered by the difficulty in adapting the complex, disconnected code. Here, we present disco, an open-source Python library that brings these techniques to the broader public","doi":"10.18653\/v1\/2023.acl-demo.14","url":"https:\/\/aclanthology.org\/2023.acl-demo.14.pdf","extracted":true,"datafile":"2023.acl.xml","authors":[{"first":"Germ\u00e1n","last":"Kruszewski"},{"first":"Jos","last":"Rozen"},{"first":"Marc","last":"Dymetman"}],"question":"\u09b8\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u0982\u09b6\u0997\u09c1\u09b2\u09cb\u09b0 ROUGE-L \u098f\u09b0 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09e6.\u09e8\u09eb\u09ed \u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09c7\u09a1\u09bc\u09c7 \u0995\u09a4 \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ?","model_id":"BanglaLLM\/BanglaLLama-3-8b-bangla-alpaca-orca-instruct-v0.0.1","model_config":"default","lang":"bengali","prompt":"\"disco: a toolkit for Distributional Control of Generative Models\" \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09af\u09bc Kruszewski,Germ\u00e1n  et al. \u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09be, \u09b8\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u0982\u09b6\u0997\u09c1\u09b2\u09cb\u09b0 ROUGE-L \u098f\u09b0 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09e6.\u09e8\u09eb\u09ed \u09a5\u09c7\u0995\u09c7 \u09ac\u09c7\u09a1\u09bc\u09c7 \u0995\u09a4 \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ? \u098f\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u09b9\u09b2\u09cb, \u09af\u09be \u0986\u09aa\u09a8\u09bf \u09b0\u09c7\u09ab\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8 \u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09c7\u09ac\u09c7 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u0964: Pre-trained language models and other generative models have revolutionized NLP and beyond. However, these models tend to reproduce undesirable biases present in their training data. Also, they may overlook patterns that are important but challenging to capture. To address these limitations, researchers have introduced distributional control techniques. These techniques, not limited to language, allow controllin","output_text":"9","output_tokens":["9","<|end_of_text|>"],"output_logits":[11.7502679825,8.3913526535],"has_fluency_mistakes":"n","has_factual_mistakes":"y"}
{"index":66,"title":"Mind Your Outliers! Investigating the Negative Impact of Outliers on Active Learning for Visual Question Answering","abstract":"Active learning promises to alleviate the massive data needs of supervised machine learning: it has successfully improved sample efficiency by an order of magnitude on traditional tasks like topic classification and object recognition. However, we uncover a striking contrast to this promise: across 5 models and 4 datasets on the task of visual question answering, a wide variety of active learning approaches fail to outperform random selection. To understand this discrepancy, we profile 8 active learning methods on a per-example basis, and identify the problem as collective outliers \u2013 groups of examples that active learning methods prefer to acquire but models fail to learn (e.g., questions that ask about text in images or require external knowledge). Through systematic ablation experiments and qualitative visualizations, we verify that collective outliers are a general phenomenon responsible for degrading pool-based active learning. Notably, we show that active learning sample efficiency increases significantly as the number of collective outliers in the active learning pool decreases. We conclude with a discussion and prescriptive recommendations for mitigating the effects of these outliers in future work.","doi":"10.18653\/v1\/2021.acl-long.564","url":"https:\/\/aclanthology.org\/2021.acl-long.564.pdf","extracted":true,"datafile":"2021.acl.xml","authors":[{"first":"Siddharth","last":"Karamcheti"},{"first":"Ranjay","last":"Krishna"},{"first":"Li","last":"Fei-Fei"},{"first":"Christopher","last":"Manning"}],"question":"\u09b8\u09b0\u09cd\u09ac\u09ae\u09cb\u099f \u09ee\u099f\u09be active learning strategies \u09ae\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09c7 \u0995\u09df\u099f\u09be\u09a4\u09c7 \u09a8\u099c\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09df\u09be \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ?","model_id":"BanglaLLM\/BanglaLLama-3-8b-bangla-alpaca-orca-instruct-v0.0.1","model_config":"default","lang":"bengali","prompt":"\"Mind Your Outliers! Investigating the Negative Impact of Outliers on Active Learning for Visual Question Answering\" \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09af\u09bc Karamcheti,Siddharth  et al. \u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09be, \u09b8\u09b0\u09cd\u09ac\u09ae\u09cb\u099f \u09ee\u099f\u09be active learning strategies \u09ae\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09c7 \u0995\u09df\u099f\u09be\u09a4\u09c7 \u09a8\u099c\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09df\u09be \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ? \u098f\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u09b9\u09b2\u09cb, \u09af\u09be \u0986\u09aa\u09a8\u09bf \u09b0\u09c7\u09ab\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8 \u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09c7\u09ac\u09c7 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u0964: Active learning promises to alleviate the massive data needs of supervised machine learning: it has successfully improved sample efficiency by an order of magnitude on traditional tasks like topic classification and object recognition. However, we uncover a striking contrast to this promise: across 5 models and 4 datasets on the task of visual question answering, a wide variety of active learning approaches fail","output_text":"80% of the time. The main culprit of this unexpecting result is outliers, which are a handful of data points that are much more out of the main distribution of the data. We show that outliers are a key factor that may lead to unexpecting performance of many Active Learning methods.","output_tokens":["80","%","\u0120of","\u0120the","\u0120time",".","\u0120The","\u0120main","\u0120culprit","\u0120of","\u0120this","\u0120un","expect","ing","\u0120result","\u0120is","\u0120out","liers",",","\u0120which","\u0120are","\u0120a","\u0120handful","\u0120of","\u0120data","\u0120points","\u0120that","\u0120are","\u0120much","\u0120more","\u0120out","\u0120of","\u0120the","\u0120main","\u0120distribution","\u0120of","\u0120the","\u0120data",".","\u0120We","\u0120show","\u0120that","\u0120out","liers","\u0120are","\u0120a","\u0120key","\u0120factor","\u0120that","\u0120may","\u0120lead","\u0120to","\u0120un","expect","ing","\u0120performance","\u0120of","\u0120many","\u0120Active","\u0120Learning","\u0120methods",".","<|end_of_text|>"],"output_logits":[9.9085235596,13.3719539642,11.7281188965,13.2614250183,14.422296524,12.3011579514,8.6083030701,8.1265487671,9.3118848801,10.0905160904,10.7582941055,7.1058750153,11.4795837402,9.1356515884,9.0694484711,11.9140233994,9.9315986633,14.1315698624,12.092924118,7.7023677826,10.9192152023,9.0116853714,9.8301229477,13.2252492905,6.620595932,10.3041629791,11.7216129303,9.7845287323,9.3124303818,9.2680263519,7.0018153191,13.0501060486,10.4723711014,10.4372310638,10.8841276169,11.1324357986,12.6237182617,12.184835434,12.8271427155,9.3252029419,9.3234863281,12.7051696777,11.5661430359,21.3437633514,10.019361496,10.5515317917,9.694360733,11.0724687576,10.3143424988,7.7875733376,9.9644184113,12.8798141479,8.9534015656,11.6637592316,18.0830039978,8.4838905334,11.2010383606,9.2803344727,9.3059940338,14.7487812042,12.855014801,14.0547523499,9.6707572937],"has_fluency_mistakes":"n","has_factual_mistakes":"y"}
{"index":67,"title":"Video-aided Unsupervised Grammar Induction","abstract":"We investigate video-aided grammar induction, which learns a constituency parser from both unlabeled text and its corresponding video. Existing methods of multi-modal grammar induction focus on grammar induction from text-image pairs, with promising results showing that the information from static images is useful in induction. However, videos provide even richer information, including not only static objects but also actions and state changes useful for inducing verb phrases. In this paper, we explore rich features (e.g. action, object, scene, audio, face, OCR and speech) from videos, taking the recent Compound PCFG model as the baseline. We further propose a Multi-Modal Compound PCFG model (MMC-PCFG) to effectively aggregate these rich features from different modalities. Our proposed MMC-PCFG is trained end-to-end and outperforms each individual modality and previous state-of-the-art systems on three benchmarks, i.e. DiDeMo, YouCook2 and MSRVTT, confirming the effectiveness of leveraging video information for unsupervised grammar induction.","doi":"10.18653\/v1\/2021.naacl-main.119","url":"https:\/\/aclanthology.org\/2021.naacl-main.119.pdf","extracted":true,"datafile":"2021.naacl.xml","authors":[{"first":"Songyang","last":"Zhang"},{"first":"Linfeng","last":"Song"},{"first":"Lifeng","last":"Jin"},{"first":"Kun","last":"Xu"},{"first":"Dong","last":"Yu"},{"first":"Jiebo","last":"Luo"}],"question":"\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09be \u09ae\u09a1\u09c7\u09b2 \u0995\u09a4\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09c7 run \u0995\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cb \u09b9\u09df ?","model_id":"BanglaLLM\/BanglaLLama-3-8b-bangla-alpaca-orca-instruct-v0.0.1","model_config":"default","lang":"bengali","prompt":"\"Video-aided Unsupervised Grammar Induction\" \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09af\u09bc Zhang,Songyang  et al. \u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09be, \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09be \u09ae\u09a1\u09c7\u09b2 \u0995\u09a4\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09c7 run \u0995\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cb \u09b9\u09df ? \u098f\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u09b9\u09b2\u09cb, \u09af\u09be \u0986\u09aa\u09a8\u09bf \u09b0\u09c7\u09ab\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8 \u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09c7\u09ac\u09c7 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u0964: We investigate video-aided grammar induction, which learns a constituency parser from both unlabeled text and its corresponding video. Existing methods of multi-modal grammar induction focus on grammar induction from text-image pairs, with promising results showing that the information from static images is useful in induction. However, videos provide even richer information, including not only static objects bu","output_text":"9t also motion and motion.","output_tokens":["9","t","\u0120also","\u0120motion","\u0120and","\u0120motion",".","<|end_of_text|>"],"output_logits":[9.659705162,10.1966142654,8.6681900024,10.1844387054,11.100933075,10.9620370865,9.8190498352,7.9862675667],"has_fluency_mistakes":null,"has_factual_mistakes":null}
{"index":68,"title":"Glot500: Scaling Multilingual Corpora and Language Models to 500 Languages","abstract":"The NLP community has mainly focused on scaling Large Language Models (LLMs) vertically, i.e., making them better for about 100 languages. We instead scale LLMs horizontally: we create, through continued pretraining, Glot500-m, an LLM that covers 511 predominantly low-resource languages. An important part of this effort is to collect and clean Glot500-c, a corpus that covers these 511 languages and allows us to train Glot500-m. We evaluate Glot500-m on five diverse tasks across these languages. We observe large improvements for both high-resource and low-resource languages compared to an XLM-R baseline. Our analysis shows that no single factor explains the quality of multilingual LLM representations. Rather, a combination of factors determines quality including corpus size, script, \u201chelp\u201d from related languages and the total capacity of the model. Our work addresses an important goal of NLP research: we should notlimit NLP to a small fraction of the world\u2019s languages and instead strive to support as many languages as possible to bring the benefits of NLP technology to all languages and cultures. Code, data and models are available at https:\/\/github.com\/cisnlp\/Glot500.","doi":"10.18653\/v1\/2023.acl-long.61","url":"https:\/\/aclanthology.org\/2023.acl-long.61.pdf","extracted":false,"datafile":"2023.acl.xml","authors":[{"first":"Ayyoob","last":"Imani"},{"first":"Peiqin","last":"Lin"},{"first":"Amir Hossein","last":"Kargaran"},{"first":"Silvia","last":"Severini"},{"first":"Masoud","last":"Jalili Sabet"},{"first":"Nora","last":"Kassner"},{"first":"Chunlan","last":"Ma"},{"first":"Helmut","last":"Schmid"},{"first":"Andr\u00e9","last":"Martins"},{"first":"Fran\u00e7ois","last":"Yvon"},{"first":"Hinrich","last":"Sch\u00fctze"}],"question":"Noise \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 chunk-level filters \u099b\u09be\u09a1\u09bc\u09be \u0985\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u0995\u09c0 \u09a7\u09b0\u09a3\u09c7\u09b0 filters \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09be \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ?","model_id":"BanglaLLM\/BanglaLLama-3-8b-bangla-alpaca-orca-instruct-v0.0.1","model_config":"default","lang":"bengali","prompt":"\"Glot500: Scaling Multilingual Corpora and Language Models to 500 Languages\" \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09cb\u09a8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b2\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09af\u09bc Imani,Ayyoob  et al. \u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09be, noise \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 chunk-level filters \u099b\u09be\u09a1\u09bc\u09be \u0985\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u0995\u09c0 \u09a7\u09b0\u09a3\u09c7\u09b0 filters \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09be \u09b9\u09df\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 ? \u098f\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u09a6\u09c7\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u09b9\u09b2\u09cb, \u09af\u09be \u0986\u09aa\u09a8\u09bf \u09b0\u09c7\u09ab\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8 \u09b9\u09bf\u09b8\u09c7\u09ac\u09c7 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09a8\u0964: The NLP community has mainly focused on scaling Large Language Models (LLMs) vertically, i.e., making them better for about 100 languages. We instead scale LLMs horizontally: we create, through continued pretraining, Glot500-m, an LLM that covers 511 predominantly low-resource languages. An important part of this effort is to collect and clean Glot500-c, a corpus that covers these 511 languages and allows us to ","output_text":"pretrain Glot500-m on it. \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae\u09c7, \u0986\u09ae\u09b0\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09bf \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be\u09b0 \u099c\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b8 \u09b8\u09b9 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09ac\u09a1\u09bc \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09aa\u09be\u09b8 \u09a4\u09c8\u09b0\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09bf, \u09af\u09c7\u09ae\u09a8 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09ac\u09a1\u09bc \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09aa\u09be\u09b8 \u09a4\u09c8\u09b0\u09bf \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09af\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09bf \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09bf \u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09a6\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b8 \u09b0\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7\u0964 \u098f\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09aa\u09be\u09b8 \u09a4\u09c8\u09b0\u09bf \u09b9\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7, \u0986\u09ae\u09b0\u09be \u098f\u099f\u09bf\u0995\u09c7 \u0986\u09b0\u0993 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ad\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8 \u09a7\u09b0\u09a3\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ab\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac\u09b9\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09b0\u09bf\u0964 \u098f\u0987 \u09ab\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u09b0\u0997\u09c1\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09c7 \u09b0\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 \u0995\u09cd\u09b2\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u0982 \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f, \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f \u09b2\u09c7\u09ae\u09bf\u09a8\u09be\u0987\u099c\u09c7\u09b6\u09a8, \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f \u099f\u09cb\u0995\u09c7\u09a8\u09be\u0987\u099c\u09c7\u09b6\u09a8, \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f \u09ac\u09c1\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u099c\u09c7\u09b6\u09a8 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f \u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09ae\u09cd\u09aa\u09bf\u0982\u0964 \u0986\u09ae\u09b0\u09be \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09bf \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be\u09b0 \u099c\u09a8\u09cd\u09af \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u099f\u09bf \u09a7\u09b0\u09a3\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ab\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09ac","output_tokens":["\u0120pre","train","\u0120Gl","ot","500","-m","\u0120on","\u0120it",".","\u